Problem 1

First, I will import and clean the data, including filtering the data to necessary items.

homicide_data =
  read.csv(
    "./data/homicide-data.csv",
    na = "Unknown") |>
  janitor::clean_names() |>
  drop_na() |>
  mutate(
    victim_last = str_to_title(victim_last),
    victim_first = str_to_title(victim_first),
    city_state = paste(city, state, sep = ", "),
    victim_age = as.numeric(victim_age),
    status = case_when(
      disposition == "Closed without arrest" ~ "Solved",
      disposition == "Closed by arrest" ~ "Solved",
      disposition == "Open/No arrest" ~ "Unsolved")) |>
  filter(!(city_state %in% c("Dallas, TX", "Phoenix, AZ", "Kansas City, MO", "Tulsa, OK"))) |>
  filter(victim_race == "White" | victim_race == "Black")

Now, I will fit a logistic regression for Baltimore, MD with status as the outcome and victim_age, victim_sex, and victim_race as predictors. I will tidy the output and obtain an estimate of the odds ratio.

regression_data =
  homicide_data |>
  mutate(
    status = case_when(
      status == "Solved" ~ 1,
      status == "Unsolved" ~ 0))

status_fit =
  glm(status ~ victim_age + victim_sex + victim_race, data = regression_data, family = "binomial") |>
  broom::tidy() |>
  mutate(OR = exp(estimate))

status_fit

Problem 2

First, I will download the weather data set as instructed.

weather_df = 
  rnoaa::meteo_pull_monitors(
    c("USW00094728"),
    var = c("PRCP", "TMIN", "TMAX"), 
    date_min = "2022-01-01",
    date_max = "2022-12-31") |>
  mutate(
    name = recode(id, USW00094728 = "CentralPark_NY"),
    tmin = tmin / 10,
    tmax = tmax / 10) |>
  select(name, id, everything())

Now, I will create a simple linear regression with tmax as the outcome and tmin and prcp as the predictors.

tmax_fit = lm(tmax ~ tmin + prcp, data = weather_df)

Now, I will pull r-squared.

r2 =
  tmax_fit |>
  broom::glance() |>
  select(r.squared)

r2
## # A tibble: 1 × 1
##   r.squared
##       <dbl>
## 1     0.916

Now, I will pull β̂ 1 and β̂ 2.

betas =
  tmax_fit |>
  broom::tidy() |>
  select(term, estimate)

beta1 = 
  betas |>
  filter(term == "tmin") |>
  select(estimate)

beta2 =
  betas |>
  filter(term == "prcp") |>
  select(estimate)

log_beta1_beta2 = log(abs(beta1 * beta2))

I will draw 5,000 bootstrap samples and produce estimates of log(β̂ 1∗β̂ 2) using broom::tidy() and pivot_wider.

prcp_tmin_bootstrap =
  weather_df |>
  modelr::bootstrap(n = 5000) |>
  mutate(
    models = map(strap, \(weather_df) lm(tmax ~ tmin + prcp, data = weather_df)),
    results = map(models, broom::tidy),
    sample_number = row_number()) |>
  unnest(results) |>
  filter(term %in% c("prcp", "tmin")) |>
  pivot_wider(
    id_cols = sample_number,
    names_from = term,
    values_from = estimate) |>
  mutate(
    log = log(abs(tmin * prcp)))

prcp_tmin_bootstrap

I will draw 5,000 bootstrap samples and produce estimates of r-squared using broom::glance.

r2_bootstrap =
  weather_df |>
  modelr::bootstrap(n = 5000) |>
  mutate(
    models = map(strap, \(weather_df) lm(tmax ~ tmin + prcp, data = weather_df)),
    results = map(models, broom::glance),
    sample_number = row_number()) |>
  unnest(results) |>
  select(sample_number, r.squared)

r2_bootstrap

Now, I will identify the 2.5% and 97.5% quantiles to provide a 95% confidence interval for r-squared and the log of B1 and B2.

r2_bootstrap_ci =
  r2_bootstrap |>
  summarize(
    ci_lower = quantile(r.squared, 0.025),
    ci_upper = quantile(r.squared, 0.975))

r2_bootstrap_ci
## # A tibble: 1 × 2
##   ci_lower ci_upper
##      <dbl>    <dbl>
## 1    0.888    0.940
prcp_tmin_bootstrap_ci =
  prcp_tmin_bootstrap |>
  summarize(
    ci_lower = quantile(log, 0.025),
    ci_upper = quantile(log, 0.975))

prcp_tmin_bootstrap_ci

I will use a data-driven modeling process to propose a regression model for birthweight. I compare my findings from two methods: first, I will create ggplots to look at trends in each variable against bwt on the y-axis and look at the strongest visual trends, and second, I will run statistical tests (correlations, t-tests, or ANOVAs depending on the type of independent variable) against bwt as the dependent variable and look at the strongest numeric correlations or largest test statistic. I expect to see consistency between the two methods (ggplots and statistics) and will include the variables with the strongest visual or numeric relationships in my model.

However, I am automatically excluding pnumlbw and pnumsga as potential independent variables because their values across the entire sample were all 0, so there cannot be any trends between them and bwt.

The following variables showed both high visual relationships from ggplots and high statistical relationships (correlations above r-squared = 0.7 or p-values below alpha = 0.05): bhead, blength, babysex, malform, frace, and mrace.

model = lm(bwt ~ bhead + blength, data = birthweight_df)
